Dinesh D’Souza argues that the West has lost the cultural confidence that once flowed from Christianity, leaving societies unable to assert a shared moral framework. He contrasts this with Islamic societies that unapologetically protect their religious character, and suggests the West once did the same. The conversation centers on whether reviving Christian principles at the heart of community life is necessary to restore social cohesion and resist cultural decay.
